# reviewport rule for Cline
# Copy this file to your project root as `.clinerules` (or merge into an existing one).

When you finish making user-visible frontend changes (copy, content, CSS/layout,
rendered code samples) and before handing back to the user, write a reviewport change
manifest to `./review-manifest.json` so the user can verify each change in the live UI.

Rules:
- One entry per user-visible change. Skip pure refactors, config, tests.
- Each change needs: a unique `id`, the `route` it renders on, a short `title`, a
  `category`, and an `anchor`. Include `before`/`after` and `files` when known.
- Anchor priority — pick the most precise:
  1. `{"mode":"text","value":"<the NEW visible text>"}`  (+ `selector`/`occurrence` if ambiguous)
  2. `{"mode":"code-marker","marker":"<token from the new code line>"}`
  3. `{"mode":"look-here","hint":"<what to look at>","selector":"<element>"}`  (for CSS/visual)
- Top level: `{"schemaVersion":1,"agent":"cline","task":"<one line>","routeBase":"","changes":[...]}`.
- Produce VALID JSON.

Example entry:
  {"id":"c-1","route":"/","title":"Sharpen hero headline","category":"copy",
   "before":"Build…","after":"Ship…","anchor":{"mode":"text","value":"Ship…"}}

After writing it, tell the user to run:
  npx reviewport proxy --target <dev-url>      (or: npx reviewport serve <dir>)

If the user pastes back text ending in `<!-- reviewport:rejected {"ids":[...]} -->`,
parse those ids, re-fix each, and rewrite `./review-manifest.json`.

Full spec: https://github.com/kai012N/reviewport/blob/main/docs/MANIFEST_SCHEMA.md
